### ── MQTT / Sensors (Development) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
###
### To test the MQTT + mock sensor flow locally on your PC:
###
### 1. Start services:
###    docker compose up -d postgres mosquitto ollama
###
### 2. Start the HomeAssistant API (this terminal):
###    dotnet run --project HomeAssistant.Presentation --launch-profile http
###
### 3. In another terminal, subscribe to mock readings:
###    docker exec -it ha-mosquitto mosquitto_sub -h localhost -t 'homeassistant/test/mock-sensors/#' -v
###
### 4. Manual advisory summary topic:
###    docker exec -it ha-mosquitto mosquitto_sub -h localhost -t 'homeassistant/garden/advice/summary' -v
###
### 5. In yet another terminal, poll sensor readings from the API:
###    Repeatedly call: GET http://localhost:5064/api/sensors (once this endpoint is implemented)
###
### Each call to GetLatestReadingsAsync will:
### - Generate 6 mock sensor readings (in Development mode)
### - Publish them to MQTT topics: homeassistant/test/mock-sensors/<pot-id>
### - You'll see them appear in the mosquitto_sub output above
###
### To verify the Zigbee2MQTT provider on a Pi with real hardware:
### - Configure actual Zigbee2MQTT topics in appsettings.json under Mqtt:SensorTopicMappings
### - Switch to Production build (which uses Zigbee2MqttSensorProvider instead of MockSensorProvider)
### - The API will subscribe to those MQTT topics and cache incoming readings
###
